 and Pastor explore the experiences of first- and second-generation Latino residents, their long-time Black neighbors, and local civic leaders seeking to build coalitions. Acknowledging early tensions between Black and Brown communities. they show how Latino immigrants settled into a new country and a new neighborhood, finding various ways to co-exist, cooperate, and, most recently, demonstrate Black-Brown solidarity at a time when both racial and ethnic communities have come under threat. Hondagneu-Sotelo and Pastor show how Latino and Black residents have practiced, and adapted innovative strategies of belonging in a historically Black context, ultimately crafting a new route to place-based identity and political representation. South Central Dreams illuminates how racial and ethnic demographic shifts—as well as the search for identity and belonging—are dramatically shaping American cities and neighborhoods around the country.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCommunitieszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aCommunity developmentzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aMinoritieszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aBlack/Brown.  aChange.  aCivics.  aCoalitions.  aCommunity Gardens.  aDemographics.  aGentrification.  aHistory.  aHomemaking.  aIdentity.  aImmigration.  aLatino.  aLos Angeles.  aMasculinities.  aNeighborhood change.  aParks.  aPlace-based racial identity.  aPolitics.  aRace and Place Identity.  aRace.  aRacial-ethnic sedimentation.  aRacism.  aSecond-generation.  aSettlement.  aSocial movements.  aSouth L.A.  aTheory.  aUrban politics.  aUrbanism.  aUrbanization.  aYouth.1 aChlala, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHondagneu-Sotelo, Pierrette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc